Recall that

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle \ln(1-x) = -x -\frac{x^2}2 -\frac{x^3}3 - \cdots,
\end{align*}

therefore

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle x \ln(1-x)= -x^2 - \frac{x^3}2 - \frac{x^4} 3-\cdots
\end{align*}

The coefficient of \emph{x}\textsuperscript{3} term is -1/2 and so the
correct answer is D.

If you don't remember the Taylor series about \emph{x} = 0 of
$\displaystyle \ln(1-x)$ you can simply re-compute it. Recall that the
Taylor series of a function $f$ about the point \emph{x} = \emph{a} is

\begin{align*}
f(a) + f'(a)(x-a) + \frac{f''(a)}{2!}(x-a)^2 + \frac{f^{(3)}(a)}{3!}(x-a)^3 + \ldots
\end{align*}

For the function

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
f(x) = \ln(1-x)
\end{align*} we have

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
f'(a) = -\frac{1}{1-a} \quad f''(a) = -\frac{1}{(1-a)^2} \quad f^{(3)}(a) = -\frac{2}{(1-a)^3}
\end{align*}
and so at \emph{a} = 0 we obtain

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
f'(0) = -1 \quad f''(0) = -1 \quad f^{(3)}(x) = -2
\end{align*}

And so the Taylor series of $\displaystyle \ln(1-x)$ around \emph{x} = 0
is

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
- x - \frac{1}{2} x^2 - \frac{1}{3}x^3 + \ldots
\end{align*}

And hence the Taylor series of $\displaystyle x \ln(1-x)$ around
\emph{x} = 0 is

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
- x^2 - \frac{1}{2} x^3 - \frac{1}{3} x^4 + \ldots
\end{align*}

And we can observe that the \emph{x}\textsuperscript{3} coefficient is
-1/2 which is the answer D.

